{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_clash_ver01/data/sn92051343/00414219597/1949060401/0137.xml":{"full_text":"SAT. JUNE 4, 1949\nTHE NEW ENGLAND BULLETIN\nPage Seven\nLE\nTS WAKE UP POLITIC ALL Y\"\nBURKE\nWA TERBUR Y SCRIBE\nCALLS ON CITIZENS\nTO USE VOTE POWER\nBy J. Edward Burke\n.Bulletin Waterbury. Correspondent\nYes, this is election year city\nelections.\nDo you realize hoyr much Ne\ngroes have been crying how we've\n\"been oppressed,, discriminated\nagainst, segregated, etc. We've\nbeen crying for opportunities. Our\nbanner has been raised very high\n\"Give us a chance, give us a\nchance!\" But, when the chance hit\nus right in the face there were\n\"very few of us who grasped it.\nFrom the time of slavery's end\n\"to this present day there have been\n-quite a few changes brought about\nand a great many of them by the\nNegroes who have tried to pro\ngress. These things did not come\nby a whole lot of gift of gab gab\netc., blah blah etc. The trouble has\nbeen that we make a great many\ncomments but too little effort.\nThere are too few Negroes who\nrealize just how important their\nvote is. They consider their vote\n\u00e0s a bothersome task, a tax, or\njust something that comes around\nonce a year.\nCartana shows that we have ap\nproximately 6500 Negroes in Wa\nterbury but it is probably true that\nut. nf those 6500 we haven't got\niKnn irnAT.!. \"Peonie who are not\n-r\u00c04--.e. al svilii TiAmme voters. It\ndoesn't cost a thing. It's but a few\nminutes walk from your home to\nthe City Hall, and takes but a few\nminutes to be made a voter. Per\nhaps some think this is not im\nportant at all. But, in a city such\nas Waterbury, votes are not only\nimportant they are essential es\nsential if we are to get the good\ngovernment that we want essen\ntial if we are to get the full meas\nure of help for the things we are\nfierhting for.\nIf your vote were not important,\nwhy would you find party workers\ngoing around telling you about how\ngreat their party is begging you\nforyour yote. This vote of ours\nJs a very ver v precious thing. BUT,\nit is not enough to vote we\nmust weigh the merits of those\ncandidates to the best of our abil\nity following their activities as\nclosely as possible. You want your\nvote to count in the right direction.\nIf we aren't careful we'll find our\nselves selling for a beer and a\nsandwich right down the river, and\nit'll be Uncle Tom right there do\ning it for you.\nProtect yourself. If you aren't\na voter become one. Set an exam\nple that cannot be ignored by the\nyouth who will be voters oi tomor\nrow. If you are a parent, start pro\ntectincr your children srive them\nthe opportunity which you didn't\nhave, or had and didn't use.\nIf your child is a grammar school\nchild, see that he goes to high\nschool.\nIf he's a high school child, see\nthat he goes to college. A lot of\npeople say \"I haven't got that kind\nof money.\" Well, maybe twenty\nyears ago that sort of thing -was\ntrue, but today there are too many\nmeans to keep a child from being\nignorant; the only way they can\npossibly be ignorant today is 'if\nyour parents, let them\" be. If you\nwould like to be a credit to the\nNegro race, take these steps to\nward fulfilling your duties, which\nare six-fold to your home, to\nvour community, to your state, to\nyour country, to the world, and to\nyourself as a member of the hu\nman race become a voter if you\nare not one, and cast that vote in\nall elections, and cast it to the very\nbest of your ability. Let's get to\ngether.\nMeet A Sweet Girl Graduate\nWATER BURY\nMMm\nWith\nEDDY BURKE\n..-wiiat vV v.-.-.-.-.-.;.y\n:;:-:v:x-.::x::\nWATERBURY CAN WELL BE PROUD of Bernice M. Wol\nfrey, daughter of Mr. and Mrs. Herbert Wolfrey, 198 Bishop St.\nBernice graduated on Monday from Virginia State College with\nhonors. While at school, she was the Editor of the College news\npaper and a member of the Alpha Kappa Alpha Sorority. She re\nceived her SP degree in Business Administration. She is a gradu\nate of Driggs Grammar School and WUby High arid was an honor\nstudent at both schools.\nMiss Wolfrey is a member of the Waterbury NAACP Youth\nCouncil.\nCHIT CHAT\nThe current business slump has\nset Scovill's off on a new plan for\ntheir salaried help a four-day\nweek to some, and an hourly pay\nbasis for others In the U. S.\n'Time-AFL-WWU negotiations the\nTJSTime Corporation won out with\ntheir proposal for a 21 cents-an-bour\npay cut against the Unions\n'demand for three additional paid\nholidays and a company-financed\nwelfare fund. It would seem that\nthe unions are ih for a turn at\nplaying the mouse The unem\nployment picture is like a see-saw\nlast week the compensation\nclaims 'filed in this area (8,663)\nshowed a decline of 4 from the\nprevious week. This week the fig\nure (9,001) is an increase of 4\nThat' odd LV is me More\nthan 360 members of the Masonic\nfraternity observed the 35th birth\nday of the Masonic Temple recent\nly in the Masons' Temple with the\nburing'of the last bond of the Tem\nple building v School today is\ngiving our children much more than\nmost of us realize, as I saw evid\nenced at the educational institute\nheld at Anderson School last week\nfor adults as well as the students\nHope you are all following the\ndevelopments and findings regard-\nto be sure that the $75,000 relief\nbudget was expended properly.\nMrs. Ruth A. Jones is superintend\nent of that department Rental\ncharges in the Fairmount Homes\ndevelopment will be lower than\noriginal estimates due to savings\neffected with regard to the site,!\ni x\nutilities services ana a contract Dia\nlower than anticipated Water\nbury has an application on file\nwith the National Housing Admin\nistration for a 10-million-dollar al\nlowance for public housing\nAt the recent national housing con\nference in Washington to discuss\nwith congressional leaders and\nother housing authorities the pros\npect of legislation being, enacted to\nprovide funds for slum clearance\nand low-cost rental housing were\nLester E. Young, chairman of the\nWaterbury Housing Authority and\nJohn Cianci, secretary whom we\nall know, or perhaps, should know\nCIO Progressive MetalworK\ners Council b\u00e9ghis their first ef\nforts to bargain.f or 40 hrs. pay for\nv i il J-f- 1 jjtm. tTn rtsv-l\n5o nrs. mis moiibii swiui Kjuaoco\nand Waterbury plants of the Amer\nican Brass Co.\nri.TTH \"NTfvrRR\nThe Good Neighbor Group held\nit --Ninth- Annual Silver Tea on\ning the Welfare Denartment. Le-1 Sunday. May 22nd at the home 01\nAMATEUR PHOTOGRAPH\n13 Q!\nThe BULLETIN Pays CASH\n-For Interesting Prctures. Send\nYours In TODAY. It May Hit\nTHE JACKPOT.\nMail To Picture Editor I\nTHE NEW ENGLAND BULLETIN\nBox 1199\nHartford, Connecticut\nManness was Chairman. 'The group\nwill meet again June 21st at the\nhome of Minnie Wolfrey, Bishop\nStreet. Martha Rice, Pearl Oliver\nand Marjorie Clapp, members of\nthe group on the sick list, are im\nproving. The Mothers Club of Sacred\nHeart Church gave a Rummage\nSale Thursday at 499 North Main\nStreet.\nOn Friday a social was given by\nthe Golden Leaves at the Ameri\ncan Legion Hall, Bishop Street. A\nwonderful time was had by all-\nThe Meteors AA presented a\nDecoration Day Dance featuring\nVirgie King and her Melody Maids\nof the Hollywood Cafe, New York.\nThe dance was held at Bellevue\nLake. A Variety Dance was held\nfrom three to seven p. m. witn\nsoftball and other forms of recrea\ntion throughout the day. There was'\na lar ere turnout and a wonderful\ntime was enjoyed at this affair,\nthe first of the season there.\nA Record Hop and a Hot Dog\nRoast was given by the NAACP\nYouth Council on Friday, May 20th\nat the Bostic Hall, Pearl St. Those\nin charge were Frank Munn,\nPresident and Lois Barnes, Chair\nman. The Baron-ettes, girls softball\nteam, opened up their season by\nbeating the Q'Ettes by the score\nof 28-13. The Baronettes club is\ncoached by Julius 'Buster Harri\nson. 1\nt The Rally to free the Ingram\nFamily had as speakers, Rev, De\nWitt Focre Mrs. Maude White\nKatz of New York City who visited\nMrs. Ingram and' Clyde Trudeau.\nof Bridgeport. Entertainment was\nby the Harmony Kings of Bristol,\nThe Women's Chorus of Water\nbury. the Jubilaires of Waterbury\nand Stanley Ralph and Rtith Cart\ner, pianists. Co-chairmen of the\nRally were Mrs. Delphia Davis and\nMrs. Anna Lou Kmch. MC was\nWallace Edward Kinch.\nSHORT STORIES?\nI've been approached by many\npeople wondering why the N. E. B.\ndoesn't carry a short story each\nweek. So, here's to all you readers.\nOur Editor, Al Duckett. has e\u00ecven\nhie the go-ahead sign to start a\ncontest for all who are interested\nto submit what they may call a\nkood short story, your own. of\nbourse. The winner will be judged\nBttictly by Mr. Duckett. Editor and\nwill have the opportunity to write\nwiTji me as guest artist witn his\nor her by-line. Now,\" if youVe got\nEometmng you really ttunk is good,\nnow is the time, start right Jiere\nwith the Bulletin and who knows,\nmaybe some day I might be ask\ning you for a job. The contest be\ngins as of today. If you have talent\ndon't hide it, no matter who you\nare. Who's going to be the winner?\nWho knows It could be you so\nsend that stuff in here and let's\nstart the ball rolling. Yes, as for\nall other items readers want to\nappear in the Bulletin, the address\nis Yours Truly, 50 Brook Street,\nWaterbury 40.\nAN APOLOGY!\nAn apology to the NAACP. I\nwish to apologize to the NAACP\nif I went too far m assuming that\nthey might aid m fighting our bat\ntle against Pete's Tavern, but\nnevertheless, I am still in great\nhopes that they might be our\nheroes. If I have assumed too much\nas a writer I wish to apologize to\nthis group, but- on the other hand,\nsince this organization is to widely\nknown for its democratic actions,\nI am more than sure that they will\nhelp to see that taverns such as\nPete's who charge us twenty cents\nfor a glass of beer which cost white\npeople ten cents, and then have the\nnerve to refuse us service alto\ngether when we object, are made\nto chang\u00e8 their policies, or be\nsquelched out of existence.\nFive-year-old James English, Jr.,\nson of Mr. and Mrs. James Eng\nlish,\" Bishop St., was entertained\n(Please Turn to Page 8)\nSAM'S TAILOR SHOP!\nPRESSING WHILE U WAIT!\n149 SOUTH MAIN STREET\nWaterbury, Connecticut\nTEL. 4-1846\nFr Young Men It's\nI'ZUCKERS CLOTHES'?\n5 at\nWatartary, Connecticut \u00cc\nMourn\nWaterburians\nScott.\nKeef ord Deaths\nWATERBURY The recent\ndeaths of two well-known citizens\nof this city have shocked the com\nmunity. Mrs. Arethea Holmes Scott, wife\nof Lloyd D. Scott,- 32 Robeson\nCourt died at her home after a\nprolonged illness of more than two\nyears. The daughter of the late\nMrs. Louise. Holmes and Rev.\nThomas Holmes, she was born in\nHawkinsville, Georgia, but had\nbeen a resident of Waterbury for 1\nthe past 25 years.\nShe was an active member, of\nMount Olive AME Zion Church and\nClock City Temple 895.\nThe deceased is survived by her\nhusband, Mr. Lloyd Scott;\" three\nchildren, Grace, Lloyd, Jr., and\nAlice; her father, Rev. Thomas\nHolmes; six sisters, Mrs. Fanny\nWhite, Mrs. Adele Emery, Mrs.\nSara Johnson, Miss Louise Holmes,\nMrs. Mattie Whedbee, and Mis 3\nJanet Holmes; four brothers, Rev.\nJohn Holmes, Moses Holmes, Davis\n'Holmes, and Simon Holmes.\nJames M. Keef ord, formerly of\nWaterbury, died in a hospital in\nNew York City where he had made\nMs home for the past three years.\nHe was the former proprietor of\nJimmy's Billiard Parlor, North\nSquare.\nSurviving is his sister, Mrs. Ma-\nbel K. Bradford, Waterbury. Fu\nneral services were held in New\nYork City.\n1\nREAD THE\nNew Englani\nULLET\nOUT EVERY\nWEDNESDAY\nIF YOUR DEALER DOESN'T\nSell The Bulletin, Send His\nName Address To The\nNEW ENGLAND BULLETIN\nMAIN OFFICE OR CALL\n7-5116-Circulation Dept.\nHartford, Connecticut\nYou'll Meet Such\nInteresting People\nAnd Make Loot To Boot\n(See Page 12) v'\nHOTEL ELTO)\nOn The 